{"comments":"Surface tension database in N/m (Newtons per meter).\n\n## What is Surface Tension?\n\nSurface tension (γ or σ) is the force per unit length acting at the\nsurface of a liquid, causing it to minimize surface area.\nSI unit: N/m (Newtons per meter) = J/m² (energy per area)\nCommon unit: mN/m (milliNewtons per meter) = dyn/cm\n\nYoung-Laplace equation: ΔP = 2γ/r (pressure difference across curved surface)\n\n## Physical Bounds\n\n- **Minimum**: ~0 N/m (some fluorinated oils approach 0.010)\n- **Maximum**: ~0.5 N/m (liquid metals like mercury)\n- **Common range**: 0.02 - 0.08 N/m\n\n## Why This Matters\n\nAt billion-agent scale, surface tension determines:\n- Droplet formation and shape (rendering rain, dew, splashes)\n- Capillary action (wicking, absorption)\n- Bubble formation and stability\n- Fluid simulation fidelity (meniscus, contact angle)\n\n## Related Papers\n\n- Stream Function Solver (free surface liquid simulation)\n- Fire-X (multi-phase fluid interactions)\n\n## Data Sources\n\nCRC Handbook, physical chemistry literature.\nAll values at 20-25°C against air unless noted.\n","declarations":[{"children":[{"comments":null,"info":{"declType":"instance","dependencies":[],"type":{"annotation":[],"contents":[{"annotation":[],"contents":[["Data","Eq"],"Eq"],"tag":"TypeConstructor"},{"annotation":[],"contents":[["Hydrogen","Schema","Physical","Fluid","SurfaceTension"],"SurfaceTension"],"tag":"TypeConstructor"}],"tag":"TypeApp"}},"sourceSpan":{"end":[156,54],"name":"../../hydrogen/src/Hydrogen/Schema/Physical/Fluid/SurfaceTension.purs","start":[156,1]},"title":"eqSurfaceTension"},{"comments":null,"info":{"declType":"instance","dependencies":[],"type":{"annotation":[],"contents":[{"annotation":[],"contents":[["Data","Ord"],"Ord"],"tag":"TypeConstructor"},{"annotation":[],"contents":[["Hydrogen","Schema","Physical","Fluid","SurfaceTension"],"SurfaceTension"],"tag":"TypeConstructor"}],"tag":"TypeApp"}},"sourceSpan":{"end":[157,56],"name":"../../hydrogen/src/Hydrogen/Schema/Physical/Fluid/SurfaceTension.purs","start":[157,1]},"title":"ordSurfaceTension"},{"comments":null,"info":{"declType":"instance","dependencies":[],"type":{"annotation":[],"contents":[{"annotation":[],"contents":[["Data","Show"],"Show"],"tag":"TypeConstructor"},{"annotation":[],"contents":[["Hydrogen","Schema","Physical","Fluid","SurfaceTension"],"SurfaceTension"],"tag":"TypeConstructor"}],"tag":"TypeApp"}},"sourceSpan":{"end":[160,67],"name":"../../hydrogen/src/Hydrogen/Schema/Physical/Fluid/SurfaceTension.purs","start":[159,1]},"title":"showSurfaceTension"}],"comments":"Surface tension in N/m [0.001, 1.0].\n\n## Bounds Rationale\n\n- Lower bound 0.001: Below perfluorohexane (~0.012)\n- Upper bound 1.0: Above molten iron (~0.86 at melting point)\n\nHigher surface tension = stronger tendency to minimize surface area.\n","info":{"dataDeclType":"newtype","declType":"data","roles":[],"typeArguments":[]},"kind":null,"sourceSpan":{"end":[154,47],"name":"../../hydrogen/src/Hydrogen/Schema/Physical/Fluid/SurfaceTension.purs","start":[154,1]},"title":"SurfaceTension"},{"children":[],"comments":"Create SurfaceTension with validation.\n","info":{"declType":"value","type":{"annotation":[],"contents":[{"annotation":[],"contents":[{"annotation":[],"contents":[["Prim"],"Function"],"tag":"TypeConstructor"},{"annotation":[],"contents":[["Prim"],"Number"],"tag":"TypeConstructor"}],"tag":"TypeApp"},{"annotation":[],"contents":[{"annotation":[],"contents":[["Data","Maybe"],"Maybe"],"tag":"TypeConstructor"},{"annotation":[],"contents":[["Hydrogen","Schema","Physical","Fluid","SurfaceTension"],"SurfaceTension"],"tag":"TypeConstructor"}],"tag":"TypeApp"}],"tag":"TypeApp"}},"kind":null,"sourceSpan":{"end":[163,49],"name":"../../hydrogen/src/Hydrogen/Schema/Physical/Fluid/SurfaceTension.purs","start":[163,1]},"title":"surfaceTension"},{"children":[],"comments":"Create SurfaceTension with clamping.\n","info":{"declType":"value","type":{"annotation":[],"contents":[{"annotatio